2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Graunt","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname, common in Scotland, where it is the name of a famous clan. It is derived from a nickname meaning ‘large’ (Anglo-Norman <i>grand</i>). In the United States the name is sometimes bestowed in honour of the Civil War general and 18th president,  Ulysses S. Grant  (  1822–85 )."],"variants":[]},{"name":"alias","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Rare, and of uncertain origin, possibly from the surname <i>Amias</i>, which is a local name for someone from Amiens in France. However, both surname and given name are rare. The ending <i>-ias</i> is found in biblical names (e.g.   Tobias  ), where it represents a Greek form of Hebrew <i>-iyah</i> ‘God’ <i>Amias</i> may sometimes have been chosen in the belief that it was a biblical name, reinforced by the fact that <i>am-</i> is the Latin root meaning ‘love’.  See also  Amiaz   and   Amyas ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":15,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":28,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":37,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas Graunt  alias Botton was born about 1300, in Burton, Hampshire, England, his father, Hool \"Bolton\" LeGraunt, was 32 and his mother, Mrs. Hool Legraunt, was 28. He had at least 1 son with Scisseley de Bryon."},"et":{"abt 1300–":"umbes 1300–Surnud","1300–Male":"1300–Surnud","1316–Female":"1316–Surnud","1336–Male":"1336–Surnud","1270–Male":"1270–Surnud","1274–Female":"1274–Surnud","1316":"1316","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1336":"1336","1300":"1300","1453":"1453","abt1336":"umbes 1336","1274":"1274","1270":"1270","abt 1300":"umbes 1300","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Burton, Buckinghamshire., England":"Burton, Hampshire, England","of Burton, Buckingham, England":"Burton, Cheshire, England"},"fi":{"abt 1300–":"noin 1300–Kuollut","1300–Male":"1300–Kuollut","1316–Female":"1316–Kuollut","1336–Male":"1336–Kuollut","1270–Male":"1270–Kuollut","1274–Female":"1274–Kuollut","1316":"1316","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1336":"1336","1300":"1300","1453":"1453","abt1336":"noin 1336","1274":"1274","1270":"1270","abt 1300":"noin 1300","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Burton, Buckinghamshire., England":"Burton, Hampshire, England","of Burton, Buckingham, England":"Burton, Cheshire, England"},"fr":{"abt 1300–":"environ 1300–Décédé","1300–Male":"1300–Décédé","1316–Female":"1316–Décédée","1336–Male":"1336–Décédé","1270–Male":"1270–Décédé","1274–Female":"1274–Décédée","1316":"1316","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1336":"13